    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on a linear regression model for some housing price data, but I've run into a snag. When I check my residuals, they're definitely not normally distributed—there's some really weird skew and some significant outliers messing with the fit. What's the best way to handle this so I don't violate the Gauss-Markov assumptions?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Dealing with non-normal residuals and outliers is common in linear regression. Consider transforming your dependent variable (housing price) using a log or square root transformation to help normalize the distribution. Alternatively, robust regression methods can be employed, as they are less sensitive to the influence of outliers compared to standard Ordinary Least Squares (OLS). Finally, examining potential influential points using Cook's distance can help you decide if any outliers should potentially be removed or modeled separately.",
      "source": "target",
