    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Log transformation sounds like a good starting point. Do you think I should also look into checking for heteroscedasticity? I'm worried that the variance isn't constant across the whole range of house values, which might be why the residuals look so messy.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you absolutely should check for heteroscedasticity, as that is a very common issue with real-world financial or housing data. Heteroscedasticity means the variance of the errors is not constant, which violates a key assumption of OLS and can lead to inefficient standard errors. You can formally test for this using the Breusch-Pagan or White test. If you confirm heteroscedasticity, using robust standard errors (like White-corrected standard errors) is a highly effective way to correct the inference without changing the main model estimates.",
      "source": "target",
